ce:section.ce:para:
Under visible light irradiation, composite catalysts consisting of ZnS and NM were employed to study the reduction performance of the photocatalysts, as shown in Fig 5a
                     . In the aqueous solution system used in this study, the main liquid-phase products of CO2 photoreduction were CH3OH and CH3CH2OH. Due to the rapid recombination of electrons and holes, as well as electron backflow, NM and ZnS produced only small amounts of CH3OH and CH3CH2OH. Compared to individual catalysts, CNM and 2ZNM exhibited improved photocatalytic performance. Among all catalysts, 2ZCNM demonstrated the most favorable catalytic performance, achieving yields of 501.57 µmol·g−1 for CH3OH and 564.70 µmol·g−1 for CH3CH2OH within 3 h, 47.04 % and 52.96 % selectivity for CH3OH and CH3CH2OH, respectively. This enhancement could be attributed to the suppression of electron-hole recombination. The introduction of ZnS significantly enhanced the photocatalytic activity. Fig. 5b depicts the influence of ZnS loading on the photocatalytic activity. As the ZnS content increases, more electrons are transferred to the surface of ZnS, where they react with CO2 and H2O to produce CH3OH and CH3CH2OH. However, as the ZnS loading continues to increase, the excess ZnS on the catalyst surface covers the active sites, becoming new composite centers and leading to the recombination of photogenerated electrons and holes on ZnS [56]. Under the same experimental conditions, no production of CH3OH and CH3CH2OH was detected when no light irradiation, no catalyst was used, or N2 was substituted for CO2. This indicates that the formation of CH3OH and CH3CH2OH originates from the reactant CO2 rather than residual organic compounds derived from catalyst decomposition or synthesis. In addition, we compared the photocatalytic CO2 reduction results (Table 1
                     ) of 2ZCNM with other representative photocatalysts. Clearly, the catalyst obtained in this study showed superior performance.
